	<a name="footnote27-22905_000_029">27.</a>
      </span>
				<p>See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/acts/3.20-21?lang=eng#19" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Acts 3:20&ndash;21</a>.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-22905_000_029"><a name="-22905_000_029">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote28-22905_000_029">28.</a>
      </span>
				<p>See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/dan/2.28,31-44?lang=eng#27" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Dan. 2:28, 31&ndash;44</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/65.2-6?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 65:2&ndash;6</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/124.45?lang=eng#44" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 124:45</a>.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-22905_000_029"><a name="-22905_000_029">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote29-22905_000_029">29.</a>
      </span>
				<p>See Bruce R. McConkie, <span class="emphasis">The Millennial Messiah</span> (1982), 672.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-22905_000_029"><a name="-22905_000_029">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote30-22905_000_029">30.</a>
      </span>
				<p><a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/james/1.6?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">James 1:6</a>.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-22905_000_029"><a name="-22905_000_029">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote31-22905_000_029">31.</a>
      </span>
				<p>See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/eph/3.17-19?lang=eng#16" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Eph. 3:17&ndash;19</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/col/2.6-7?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Col. 2:6&ndash;7</a>.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-22905_000_029"><a name="-22905_000_029">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote32-22905_000_029">32.</a>
      </span>
				<p>See &ldquo;Some Thoughts on Temples, Retention of Converts, and Missionary Service,&rdquo; <span class="emphasis">Ensign,</span> Nov. 1997, 51; also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/jacob/6.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Jacob 6:7</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/moro/6.4?lang=eng#3" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moro. 6:4</a>.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-22905_000_029"><a name="-22905_000_029">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote33-22905_000_029">33.</a>
      </span>
				<p><span class="emphasis">Hymns,</span> no. 85; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/28.27-30?lang=eng#26" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 28:27&ndash;30</a>.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-22905_000_029"><a name="-22905_000_029">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote34-22905_000_029">34.</a>
      </span>
				<p>See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/jacob/3.2?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Jacob 3:2</a>.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-22905_000_029"><a name="-22905_000_029">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote35-22905_000_029">35.</a>
      </span>
				<p><a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/hel/5.12?lang=eng#11" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Hel. 5:12</a>. Remember also that a wise man builds his house upon a rock and not upon shifting sand (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/7.24-27?lang=eng#23" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 7:24&ndash;27</a>).</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-22905_000_029"><a name="-22905_000_029">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote36-22905_000_029">36.</a>
      </span>
				<p><a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/hel/7.5?lang=eng#4" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Hel. 7:5</a>.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-22905_000_029"><a name="-22905_000_029">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote37-22905_000_029">37.</a>
      </span>
				<p>Whether things seem &ldquo;fair&rdquo; relate to the limits of one&rsquo;s perspective. Paul taught, &ldquo;If in this life only we have hope in Christ, we are of all men most miserable&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/1-cor/15.19?lang=eng#18" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Cor. 15:19</a>).</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-22905_000_029"><a name="-22905_000_029">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote38-22905_000_029">38.</a>
      </span>
				<p>Harry Kemp, &ldquo;God the Architect,&rdquo; in James Dalton Morrison, ed.,<span class="emphasis"> Masterpieces of Religious Verse</span> (1948), 46&ndash;47.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-22905_000_029"><a name="-22905_000_029">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote39-22905_000_029">39.</a>
      </span>
				<p>Compared with the omniscience of our Creator, we know relatively little about dinosaurs or the details of the Creation, for example. But this we do know: &ldquo;Verily I say unto you, in that day when the Lord shall come, he shall reveal all things&mdash;things which have passed, and hidden things which no man knew, things of the earth, by which it was made, and the purpose and the end thereof&mdash;things most precious, things that are above, and things that are beneath, things that are in the earth, and upon the earth, and in heaven&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/101.32-34?lang=eng#31" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 101:32&ndash;34</a>; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/121.29-32?lang=eng#28" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 121:29&ndash;32</a>).</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-22905_000_029"><a name="-22905_000_029">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote40-22905_000_029">40.</a>
      </span>
				<p>See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/11.16-17?lang=eng#15" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 11:16&ndash;17</a>.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-22905_000_029"><a name="-22905_000_029">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote41-22905_000_029">41.</a>
      </span>
				<p>Virginia H. Pearce, in <span class="emphasis">Why I Believe</span> (2002), 245&ndash;46.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-22905_000_029"><a name="-22905_000_029">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote42-22905_000_029">42.</a>
      </span>
				<p>Personal correspondence, 15 Jan. 2002.</p>
			</li>
			<li class="footnote " id="-22905_000_029"><a name="-22905_000_029">&nbsp;</a>
				<span class="label">
	<a name="footnote43-22905_000_029">43.</a>
      </span>
				<p>Our mortal probation has been likened to the second act of a three-act play. When the curtain comes down on act two, the play is not over. Without the vision gained from acts one and three, the second act could seem either too short, too long, too hard, or too confusing. When we know about all three acts, the second act acquires greater significance. Thus the need for an eternal perspective.</p>
			</li>
		</ol>
                                        
